title: For Trade:  WTT Savage mfg. Lee Enfield No. 4 Mk I* Lend Lease rifle
postcontent: I've got a Lee Enfield No.4 MkI* rifle that was made in July or August of 1943 for the UK during WWII under the Lend Lease Act. It bears the US Property mark on the left side of the receiver wall. The No.4 MkI* was a wartime variation where a number of bells and whistles were eliminated to reduce cost and expedite production. While Savage did produce some standard No.4 Mk I rifle in 1942, they are extremely rare. As such, this rifle has a two position flip rear sight (rather than the adjustable ladder type), a simplified bolt release mechanism, and a handful of other minor differences. I'd like to trade for another C&R rifle or handgun. Send me a PM and feel free to make an offer, I'm open to anything! I've got a C&R license and will need to complete a bill of sale. I'm also willing to ship to other C&Rs or FFLs. This rifle is in good shape. There is some pitting on the receiver that appears to have been parked over during factory through repair (FTR or -> mark). While I've not shot this rifle, the bore is in good shape and it should be a good shooting rifle. It has a No 1 magazine, but it fits well. The bolt does not match the receiver and the stock has a BLO finish but not is not the original finish. The wood also appears to have been sanded years ago. postcontent: Looking for a unique gift for the Deadpool fan in your life? How about this great custom Deadpool Colt 45 New Agent was created by Whiskey Tango Firearms in Sarasota, FL and is brand new, never fired. While you may not want this to be your carry gun it is a great collectors piece. This item will only be sold to verified Florida resident who also holds a CCP. Deadpool could easily be referred to as the antithesis of all things superhero, and yet the movie’s namesake did have a bit of hero in him (sort of). The movie was released immediately prior to Valentine’s Day 2016 and grossed $363.1 million here in the United States, pulling in another $419.3 million in foreign countries. Those numbers gave it a financial boost higher than all X-Men movies and although there is more, you’re not here for a movie recap. In the wake of Deadpool’s popularity, gun company Whiskey Tango Foxtrot recently unveiled their ode to the smart-assed vigilante: a Deadpool-themed pistol.Whiskey Tango Foxtrot chose a Colt 1911 and finished it as is befitting, well, Deadpool. The pistol has a red battleworn finish – because what other color would it be – and the mag is marked down one side with “chimichanga”. After all, as any true Deadpool fan knows, he loves saying the word…”Don’t even like chimichangas all that much. I just love saying it. Chimichanga. Chimichanga. Chimichanga” (Yeah, he said it. Check out “Cable and Deadpool”, Volume 1, #13). But the custom grips just might be the coolest part. The 1911’s grips are black with “Deadpool’s Gun” scrawled in white across the top and a red sketch of the masked man in question’s face which just happens to be reminiscent of his belt buckle, too. Then again, “Smile, Wait for Flash” is engraved into the muzzle. Basically, you don’t just want this gun. You need this gun.Located in the SW Florida area and willing to meet near any local Sheriff's or City Police Station for your safety and mine.Original Specs:New Agent .45 ACP 3 Inch Blue Barrel Trench-Style Sights Rosewood Grips 7 Round Mag, 1911 CompactSeries 80 firing system. Aluminum alloy receiver with anodized black finish and carbon steel slide with blued finish. Features Trench-style sight, enhanced hammer and 3-hole aluminum trigger. Standard grip safety and 1918 style safety lock. Stainless steel bushingless barrel with lowered and flared ejection port. Slim-fit rosewood grips.

title: For Sale:  Brass Processing
postcontent: What is the worst part of reloading ammo?  Brass processing...  If you have brass and dont feel like processing it, let me do it for you.  I will do the following with your brass:  deprime, resize, trim when/if needed, chamfur, debur, remove primer pocket crimps, (on military brass), check each piece in an LE Wilson case length gauge and then tumble/polish in stainless steel media.  If you want your brass primed so all you have to do is load, I will do that for you as well.  Prices are listed below.I will process 308, 5.56/223, 300 blackout, 45/70 Govt, 45 acp, 9mm, 40/10mm, 357/38, 44special/44mag.  Pistol brass is $.03 per round.  Non military rifle brass is $.05 per piece. Military brass,(crimped primer pocket), is $.06 per piece.If you want your brass primed and have primers, add $.02 per piece.  If you want your brass primed and I supply the primers, add $.05 per round.  I will use either CCI or Winchester primers.Want 5.56/223 brass converted into 300 Blackout?  I will do that too, prices are below.$.05 per piece of non military rifle brass.  $5 per 100, $25 per 500 and $50 per 1000$.08 per piece of military rifle brass due to primer pocket crimp removal.  $8 per 100, $40 per 500 and $80 per 1000payment will be due when the brass is returned to you.

I have personally owned a “JM” stamped Marlin Mod. 1895 LTD III 18 ½” octagonal barrel which is the same exact rifle as this one and there is absolutely no difference in quality in both aesthetic and functional terms.  In other words, the "JM" stamped barrel rifle I had just like this current production was in no way any better quality than this one. There was only a year back around 2009/2010 when these quality issues came up but it seems many are still stuck on that reputation. These currently made Marlins are every bit as well built as the Marlins were before they came under new ownership and there are lots of reviews on Youtube that attest to this.
